<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pressure by U.S. `Conservative Forces' Denounced </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2201050594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0450 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2201050594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Conservative Forces Must Give Up Reckless Racket of </F>
Pressure" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, January 22 (KCNA) -- Some conservative 
forces of the United States, slinging mud at the contents of 
agreement at the New York contact between the DPRK and the 
United States at the end of last year, are crying that 
compromise does not deserve welcome and continued pressure must 
be put on North Korea. And some paid media of the United States 
urge the DPRK to accept a special inspection, spreading the 
rumor that it agreed to accept routine and ad hoc inspections at 
the New York contact. 
  This is an act of throwing a wet blanket over the solution 
of the nuclear issue the way of which has been paved with so 
much efforts; it cannot be construed otherwise than a folly of 
those who do not know the essential nature of the nuclear issue 
or the direction of its solution but seek other purpose, says 
NODONG SINMUN in a commentary today. 
  The news analyst notes: 
  The nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula was caused by the 
introduction of nuclear weapons into South Korea by the United 
States. It is also the United States which complicated the 
situation by bringing forward "suspected nuclear development by 
the North". 
  Thus the nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula is a matter 
to 
be solved between the United States and the DPRK in view of its 
origin and background of its complexity today and the DPRK and 
the United States have the authority to solve it. 
  For the United States to remove the nuclear threat to the 
DPRK and renounce its hostile policy to stifle the DPRK is the 
precondition for a fundamental solution of the nuclear issue 
and a matter of clearing the debt owed by the United States to 
the DPRK down through history. 
  The DPRK agreed with the United States on the matter of 
inspection because we took into account the fact that the U.S. 
side accepted our formula of package deal and proposal for both 
sides to move simultaneously and manifested its willingness to 
discontinue the "Team Spirit" joint military exercises this year 
and hold the third-round DPRK-USA talks. 
  As for the inspection we intend to allow this time, it is an 
inspection needed merely for the guarantee of the continuity of 
safeguards according to the promise we made to the United States 
when we suspended temporarily the effectuation of our 
withdrawal from the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty [NPT] for 
the solution of the nuclear issue through negotiations. 
  The conception of the inspection for the continuity of 
safeguards is a new one that originated from our special 
position in the state of temporary stop of the effectuation of 
the withdrawal from NPT. The inspection for the continuity of 
safeguards is, therefore, quite different from the routine and 
ad hoc inspections pursuant to the obligation under the NPT and, 
moreover, the "special inspection" cannot be an object of debate. 
  The DPRK is in a state of temporary suspension of the 
effectuation of its withdrawal from the NPT. Therefore we are 
not under obligation to implement the safeguards agreement like 
a full-fledged signatory. 
  This notwithstanding, the anti-dialogue forces of the United 
States, setting in motion intelligence plotters and paid 
trumpeters, are painting an exaggerated picture of the fact as 
if the U.S. side has made a unilateral compromise and crying 
that the DPRK must be made to undergo the routine and ad hoc 
inspections and "special inspection" of the International Atomic 
Energy Agency first. This is an imprudent act that does not 
hold water. 
  That the rightwing conservative forces of the United States 
are crying for pressure by demanding even the "special 
inspection" cannot be construed otherwise than an attempt to 
bring the situation to a catastrophe by totally driving the DPRK 
out of the NPT. This real intention is to break up the 
DPRK-U.S. talks at any cost and persistently pursue the hostile 
policy to stifle the DPRK. 
  We will counter toughness with toughness and our tough will 
will be manifested more strongly in practice than in word. 
  If the U.S. hard-line conservative forces do not want to 
regret for their act tomorrow, they should act with discretion 
before it is too late. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

