<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Treasury Secretary's Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fujii Briefs Bentsen on `Turmoil' </H4>
<F P=102> OW2301061194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0537 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2301061194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 23 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii opened a meeting with U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd 
Bentsen on Sunday [23 January] with an explanation of Japan's 
current political turmoil. The meeting, which began at 2 P.M., 
is to be followed by a meeting of Bentsen and Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa at the premier's official residence at 4 P.M. 
  Greeting Bentsen at his office in the presence of reporters, 
the finance minister said he recognized that the defeat of the 
government's political reform bills "has caused you concern" and 
said he would explain the matter. The rejection of the bills 
Friday in the House of Councillors is expected to complicate 
Hosokawa's efforts to introduce economic stimulus measures in 
time for a February 11 summit between Hosokawa and President 
Bill Clinton in Washington. 
  Bentsen stopped over in Tokyo on Saturday night on his way 
home from a tour of Russia and Asia. His talks with Hosokawa 
and Fujii are expected to focus on efforts to reach an agreement 
in bilateral trade talks in time for the summit. 

</TEXT>

