<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, Washington Coordinate Nuclear Stance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2401020994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0203 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States held working-level coordination sessions on the 
North Korean nuclear issue over the weekend as Pyongyang and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) are engaged in 
inspection negotiations. 
  Tom Hubbard, deputy assistant secretary of State and top 
U.S. 
representative to contacts with North Korea, flew into Seoul on 
Sunday and met with Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu and other 
South Korean working-level officials. Hubbard accompanied 
Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen on a leg of his Asian trip and 
flew in separately to Seoul to consult on the nuclear issue, 
Ministry officials said. He leaves for Washington on Monday 
afternoon. 
  Pyongyang-IAEA negotiations on resuming inspections are 
dragging on beyond expectations and the two sides are likely to 
meet again sometime soon. 
  If these talks go well and Pyongyang reopens inter-Korean 
dialogue, the United States is expected to hold high-level talks 
with North Korea for comprehensive discussions, including 
relations improvement. 

</TEXT>

