<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Plans Worldwide Campaign on Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2501083994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Jan 
94 Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2501083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Keidanren [the Federation of Economic 
Organizations of Japan] plans to seek cooperation from economic 
organizations in the United States and European nations in 
issuing a joint statement calling on industrialized nations to 
implement their respective trade policies in line with accords 
that were concluded among negotiating nations at the end of the 
multilateral trade negotiations (the Uruguay Round of GATT). 
There have been reports that protectionism has been emerging in 
the United States where the U.S. Government and some members of 
Congress have been exploring ways to revive the Super 301 
provision of the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act. In reaction, the 
Keidanren has concluded that as a Japanese economic 
organization, it needs to work to block those U.S. moves toward 
protectionism and to call for the promotion of free trade. The 
Keidanren intends to set up a task force comprised of officials 
from major industries and enter specific consultations with 
economic organizations in the United States and European nations. 
  A plan under study by the Keidanren is that the Keidanren, 
the National Association of Manufacturers (NAM) in the United 
States, and the Union des Industries de la Communaute Europeenne 
(UNICE) [Industrial Union of the European Community] will issue 
a joint statement this spring at the earliest. With the Uruguay 
Round accords set to go into effect in mid-1995, there is a fear 
that European nations and the United Stats would take measures 
to slap sanctions against their trade partners based on 
bilateralism in the intervening time. The Keidanren, therefore, 
intends to call on the U.S. and European governments to rule out 
protectionism and adhere to the spirit of the accords. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

