<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Turmoil's Effect on U.S. Talks Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201025094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 22 
Jan 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2201025094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Jan 94 Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] With the political reform bills having been 
rejected by the House of Councillors, the outlook for the 
Japan-U.S. summit on 21 February, as well as for the ongoing 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, looks uncertain. A 
vice-ministerial-level meeting is set for 23 January in 
Washington to discuss government procurements and other matters, 
but negotiations in all sectors are experiencing very rough 
sailing over issues like U.S. demands for numerical targets. 
  Meanwhile, regarding to the impact which the current 
political chaos will have on the talks, there are now two 
contrasting views emerging within the Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs [MOFA] -- one predicts "the United States will push 
hard, becoming despaired of the Hosokawa government," and the 
other says "they will soften their position out of consideration 
for the chaotic political situation in Japan." 
  The United States is now beginning to show irritation over 
the negotiations which are making slow progress. Secretary of 
Treasury Lloyd Bentsen will arrive in Japan on 23 January. U.S. 
Trade Representative Micky Kantor has expressed his intention to 
visit Japan. The country is calling on Japan to make a 
political decision to reach a breakthrough in the talks. 
  Meanwhile Hiroshi Kumagai, minister of international trade 
and industry, insists "there is no discrepancy in views between 
the government and bureaucrats." But according to a senior MOFA 
official, there are increasing views in Japan that because of 
the problem raised by the political reform issue, "it is now 
possible Japan's political alternatives will narrow." 
  An official of the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry was perplexed, saying: "If revised political reform 
bills are promptly adopted, there will be no major impact on the 
negotiations. But if this situation leads to a weakening of the 
coalition government by the Social Democratic Party of Japan 
breaking up, or leads to the fall of Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa from power, there is no telling what will happen to the 
talks." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

