<H3> <TI>   DPRK Attempts `To Normalize' Australian Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2101134894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 4 </F>

<F P=103> OW2101134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mariko Horikawa] </F>
  [Text] Sydney, 20 Jan -- On 20 January, an Australian 
Foreign Ministry source told YOMIURI SHIMBUN that the DPRK 
(North Korea) recently contacted Australia in an attempt to 
normalize its ties with Australia and that both countries held 
unofficial meetings in third nations. The Australian Foreign 
Ministry is paying attention to the fact that North Korea has 
contacted Australia while the DPRK's discussions with the United 
States and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) are 
coming to their final stages. 
  Australia and North Korea established diplomatic ties in 
1974. Relations between the two countries were ruptured because 
North Korea had one-sidedly closed its embassy in Australia and 
deported Australian diplomats from North Korea. 
  According to an Australian Foreign Ministry spokesman and 
diplomatic sources in Australia, North Korea took the initiative 
in contacting Australia and high-level diplomats of both 
countries held meetings at Australian embassies in Bangkok and 
Jakarta between late last month and early this month. 
  In the meetings, it is said that North Korea called for 
normalization of diplomatic ties and that Australia, as a 
condition for normalizing diplomatic ties, demanded that North 
Korea accept nuclear inspections by an international 
organization and that it promote discussions with the United 
States and the ROK. Australia says it informed Japan, the 
United States and the ROK about details of the meetings. 
  In the past, Australia and North Korea promoted partial 
diplomatic exchanges in Beijing and other places. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

