<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata on Possibility of Compromise With LDP </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201134594 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2201134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a news conference on 21 January at the Diet 
building, Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] leader Tsutomu Hata 
(who is foreign minister and concurrently deputy prime 
minister), commented on the possibility of taking the political 
reform bills to a joint conference of the two houses for 
discussion. He said: "Privately, I can accept any (compromise). 
The most important thing is to change the election system." In 
this way, he explained his view that the ruling coalition 
parties should try to have the political reform bills approved 
even at the risk of having to accept all the demands of the 
Liberal Democratic Party for revision of the bills. 
  Moreover, regarding how the government should deal with the 
situation if the bills are scrapped, Hata said: "We should not 
create a (political) void because we have a pile of work to do. 
However, since the political reform bills are worth making an 
appeal to the confidence of the whole nation, I will not rule 
out any possibilities." In this way, he referred to the 
possibility of dissolving the lower house and holding a general 
election. 

</TEXT>

