<F P=102>  OW2201022894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 22 
Jan 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2201022894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Jan 94 Morning </F>
Edition] 
  [Text] On the evening of 21 January, State Minister (in 
charge of political reform) Sadao Yamahana and Minister of Home 
Affairs Kanju Sato held a joint news conference at the Ministry 
of Home Affairs. 
  When asked if they were ready to resign as a result of the 
upper house's disapproval of the political reform bills, State 
Minister Yamahana denied his immediate resignation, stating: "I 
think I should carefully consider if it is appropriate to resign 
right now. I have to consult with the ruling parties about this. 
In fact, I am not allowed to determine my course of action at 
my own discretion." 
  Minister of Home Affairs Sato said: "I have the primary 
responsibility for the enactment of the reform bills. I should 
fulfill my duties by trying my best as a cabinet member at least 
until 29 January (when the extraordinary Diet session closes)." 

