<F P=102>  SK2401105994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1028 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 24 (KCNA) -- The people of the 
northern half of Korea are bitterly condemning the inhuman act 
of the Kim Yong-sam traitorous clique in blocking the Seoul trip 
of a mourners' group of the North for Rev. Mun Ik-hwan. 
  The director of the Kim Chong-tae General Electric 
Locomotive 
Works, Pak Su-pom, branded the act of the Kim Yong-sam clique as 
an inhuman act of fascist hooligans who take no account of the 
beautiful manners and customs handed down through generations 
and elementary civility and morality. 
  He said: 
  "The South Korean puppet clique mumbled about the `nuclear 
issue' and `an organization profiting the enemy.' It is really a 
far-fetched argument and an expression of a vicious scheme to 
dampen the nation's fervor of reunification, delay the country's 
reunification and finally break off the ties of the nation". 
  He warned that a sledge-hammer blow will be dealt at the Kim 
Yong-sam clique, the enemy with whom our nation cannot live 
under the same sky. 
  Yi Song-pong, chief pastor of the Pongsu Church, Pyongyang, 
said: 
  "By not allowing delegates of the North to go to Seoul to 
mourn the deceased, the Kim Yong-sam fascist clique stripped 
themselves bare as a group of barbarians ignoring human 
morality." 
  He said Rev. Mun Ik-hwan was a patriotic champion of 
reunification who devotedly struggled for the reunification of 
the country and democratization of society in South Korea for 
many years. He pointed out that the "civilian" signboard hung 
out by the Kim Yong-sam clique was false and it was a group of 
traitors who did not want national reconciliation and 
reunification. 
  "I join the religious men in declaring to the world that the 
Kim Yong-sam fascist clique is a group of truculent, despicable 
traitors who must no longer be left in this world where only 
love, harmony and trust must prevail and, on this land of our 
nation," he added. 

</TEXT>

