<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Rejects Chondoist Move for N-S Contact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2601115194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1139 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2601115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 26 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
Government will not approve the move of South and North Korean 
Chondogyo [Chondoist] organizations to have a contact to discuss 
the possible joint sponsorship of ceremonies marking the 
centenary of the Donghak peasants revolution. 
  "Any visit to the South by North Korean Chondogyo officials 
and a South-North Chondogyo contact to discuss the visit are not 
permissible," a National Unification Board official said on 
Tuesday. He said such a move runs counter to the government 
policy of withholding all travels back and forth between the two 
sides due to the nuclear issue. 
  The central headquarters of Chondogyo, an indigenous 
religious organization, formally asked the unification board 
earlier in the day to send to the North its reply that they had 
accepted the North Korean Chondogyo proposal to have a 
working-level contact at Panmunjom on Feb. 3. 
  In a telephone message to the South's Chondogyo on Jan. 24, 
Yu Mi-yong, guidance chairman of the North Korean Chondogyo, 
offered to have a working-level contact at Panmunjom. 

</TEXT>

