<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Urges Participation in North Development </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2401045194 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 24 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401045194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Kim Hyon-ho] </F>
  [Text] The ROK, China, and North Korea are now discussing 
the details of the ROK's technological and capital investment in 
the project of expanding North Korea's Najin Port and 
constructing a railroad. 
  Liu Baisong, president of the Northeast Asia Railway and 
Port 
Corporation, Ltd. of Jilin, China, came to the ROK on 20 January 
to discuss this matter. He said on 23 January: "The Najin Port 
development project is supposed to be jointly promoted by China 
and North Korea, and North Korea has expressed its position that 
it does not oppose ROK participation in the project in a joint 
venture with China." He also said that he had sounded out ROK 
enterprises like Daewoo and Samsung on their intention to 
participate in the project during his visit to the ROK and that 
they "had expressed their intent to actively participate." 
  China is also asking ROK companies to make joint investments 
in the construction of a 5 km-long borderline railway connecting 
China's Hunchun and North Korea's Hunyung. 
  The project of enlarging the No. 3 and No. 4 Piers of Najin 
Port and equipping them with modern facilities requires a total 
amount of $60 million, and China wants the ROK to invest 
approximately $30 million in the project. 
  North Korea hopes to begin construction in April, and China 
plans to start in June after confirming ROK participation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

