<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Automakers Seek Ways To Sell in PRC Legally </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2401024494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0215 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401024494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 24 (YONHAP) -- Korean automakers, to 
cope with moves by the Chinese Government to curb illegal 
imports, are looking for ways to export vehicles to China 
legally. The Chinese administration on auto imports says that 
1,346 Korean automobiles were sold through official channels for 
14.1 million U.S. dollars in January-September last year, 
according to industry sources Monday. 
  In the nine months, the Chinese bought 58,660 Japanese 
vehicles, the highest figure, followed by Russian vehicles at 
39,651, German at 33,774, French at 20,589 and American at 
6,184. Italy placed low with 1,224 vehicles. The Korean share 
of the Chinese import market was 2.3 percent of the Japanese 
share and 21.8 percent of the U.S. share. The real number of 
Korean vehicles sold in China last year is assumed to be nearly 
50,000 (new and used), the sources said. 
  The Chinese Government bans imports of completely assembled 
automobiles in principle but legally purchases nearly 200,000 a 
year with a 180 percent to 220 percent tax by barter or for 
official use. It is estimated that 500,000 to 600,000 foreign 
automobiles are imported by China through legal and illegal 
channels each year. 
  The Chinese Government partly allowed private dealers to 
import vehicles in January, lowered the tax to 80 percent 
minimum and gave a quotas by country. Since it has decided to 
exclude from the quotas nations continuing to export to the 
Chinese market through illegal channels, Korean automakers must 
find new ways to sell in China, a source said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

