<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Businesswoman Ordered Arrested on Fraud Charges </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2401140994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1028 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 24 (YONHAP) -- The Seoul Prosecution on 
Monday afternoon placed under arrest Chang Yong-cha on charges 
of fraud and violating the bad check control law. The 
prosecution charge said Chang last October illegally withdrew 
from the Apkujong branch of the Seoul Trust Bank 3 billion won 
belonging to Ms. Ha Chong-im without the depositor's permission. 
Chang is also suspected of cheating 7.75 billion won out of the 
Sampo Mutual Trust Fund with the false promise of giving the 
fund a large deposit. The charge also said that when she was 
heading Yupyong Corp. as its chairwoman last October, the corp. 
issued a 500-million-won note but failed to honor it. 
  A law stipulates that a person found guilty of fraud 
involving more than 5 billion won is to be given a term of five 
years to life. Besides, she had five years and two more months 
to serve when she was paroled in 1992 from prison. She was 
serving a 15-year term over a 1982 financial scandal. 
  Meanwhile, the Justice Ministry on Monday afternoon 
retracted 
the parole granted to Chang in 1992, obliging her to serve out 
the remaining term. 
  A ministry official said that by law a parole may be 
cancelled if the parolee fails to behave properly or engages in 
abnormal conducts. "We have cancelled her parole upon she was 
arrested," the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

