<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Natural Gas Production Reportedly To Double </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2601045794 Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA in English 12 
Jan 94 p 12 </F>

<F P=103> BK2601045794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Energy estimates that the 
production of natural gas will be increased to 80 million cubic 
feet [cu ft] per day from the present ceiling of 40 million. 
  Myanmar Oil and Gas Enterprise, in this open season, has 
increased its natural gas production and test wells are being 
drilled in addition to the existing four. Production from 
Aphyauk Gas Well alone could reach the 80 million cubic feet per 
day very soon. The gas thus produced will be transported to 
Yangon through 14 in. pipes, and from here [Yangon] to Sittaung 
and Myainggale through a network of 10 in., eight in. and six 
in. pipes. The laying of pipelines in now under way. On 
completion, natural gas will be conveyed to the gas-driven 
electric power station in Ywama and the cement factory in 
Myainggale. A pipeline is also being laid across the Irrawaddy 
River at Prome-Myanaung crossing. This pipeline will carry gas 
to the cement plant at Kyangin, the methanol plant at Seiktha 
and the electric power station at Myanaung. 
  At present, the 40 million cu ft per day production from 
four 
wells is being piped to industries in Yangon, Sittaung Paper 
Mill and Thaketa Power Station as well as to the power station 
at Shwedaung. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

