<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Burma </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rangoon Fires Leave Over 5,000 Homeless </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2401150394 Rangoon Radio Burma in Burmese 1330 GMT 24 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2401150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rangoon Radio Burma </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Burmese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A fire which broke out in the house of U Ohn Maw 
Htut at No. 610, Third Aye Street, Fourth Ward, Hlaing Township, 
Yangon [Rangoon] Division, at 1345 gutted over 700 houses 
leaving more than 5,100 people from 1,200 households homeless. 
The fire spread from First Aye to Ninth Aye Streets in Fourth 
Ward, Hlaing River Road, Khangon First and Second Streets, and 
Aungmingala First Street. Fire engines from around Yangon 
Division rushed to the scene to put out the fire. Lieutenant 
General Myo Nyunt, commander of Yangon military command, and 
responsible personnel supervised the fire fighting efforts and 
the fire was finally brought under control at 1530. 
  Lt. Gen. Khin Nyunt, secretary-1 of the State Law and Order 
Restoration Council [SLORC], accompanied by Lieutenant Colonel 
Pe Nyein, director general of the SLORC office, arrived at the 
scene this evening and were briefed by responsible personnel. 
Lt. Gen. Khin Nyunt gave detailed instructions to responsible 
personnel in order to provide temporary shelter for fire 
victims, to provide health care, distribute relief goods and 
food, open special cooperative shops and trade departments, and 
to take a census of students affected by the fire to make 
arrangements for them to attend classes as soon as possible. 
The secretary-1 and responsible personnel next inspected the 
fire ravaged scene in Hlaing Station Road and left after giving 
necessary instructions. 
  Similarly, at 1653, a fire broke out in the house of U Aye 
Thein at No. 615, BOC corner, Station Road, Nantagon Ward, 
Insein Township. The fire gutted 12 houses leaving 89 persons 
from 12 households homeless and causing damage of about 1 
million kyats. The fire victims were temporary sheltered at 
Saywingaba Arlein Ngasint pagoda compound. 
  Authorities concerned have taken action against the owners 
of 
the two houses where the fires started. 

</TEXT>

