<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sirivut Receives UN Envoy for Human Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2401115294 Phnom Penh AKP in English 1015 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2401115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh AKP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh AKP January 24 -- Prince Norodom Sirivut, 
vice prime minister and minister for foreign affairs and 
international cooperation, met here on Saturday [22 January] Mr. 
Michael Kirby, special UN envoy for human rights, who is now on 
a visit to Cambodia. 
  Australian Michael Kirby, appointed last November as the 
United Nations special representative for human rights in 
Cambodia, arrived in Phnom Penh on Friday [21 January] and is 
due to begin looking into Cambodia's human rights situation as 
part of a week-long fact- finding mission aimed at strengthening 
human rights education. 
  Speaking to his guest, Prince Norodom Sirivut welcomed the 
Cambodia's visit by Mr. Michael Kirby on his human rights 
mission in the country, saying the issue of human rights in 
Cambodia [word indistinct] to be improved. 
  He thanked the United Nations for its concern and assistance 
to the improvement of human rights in Cambodia and pledged to 
support and create favourable conditions to the UN Human Rights 
Center to fulfill its mission in Cambodia. 
  Mr. Kirby informed the prince that his mission in Cambodia 
was to keep contact with the government and people of Cambodia 
on human rights issue and help the latter to respect the human 
rights. 
  Mr. Kirby will to make a report on the human right situation 
in Cambodia at the UN [words indistinct] the 50th meeting of the 
UN Human Rights Committee. 
  He also asked Prince Sirivut to send a high-power delegation 
of Cambodia to participate in the (?meeting to be) held in 
Geneva in (?February). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

